00:37:15,840 --> 00:37:16,540
and so forth.

962
00:37:16,680 --> 00:37:17,460
We have a pretty good idea

963
00:37:17,460 --> 00:37:18,140
what's going to happen,

964
00:37:18,320 --> 00:37:19,960
but we want to describe this

965
00:37:19,960 --> 00:37:21,920
using the laws of mechanics

966
00:37:21,920 --> 00:37:22,720
and using,

967
00:37:22,720 --> 00:37:23,240
in particular,

968
00:37:23,340 --> 00:37:24,600
the principle of least action

969
00:37:26,080 --> 00:37:26,580
or,

970
00:37:26,580 --> 00:37:27,620
more specifically,

971
00:37:27,920 --> 00:37:29,480
the Euler-Lagrange equations

972
00:37:29,480 --> 00:37:31,040
which follow from the principle of least action.

973
00:37:31,060 --> 00:37:33,120
All right,

974
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:34,160
so let's see if we can

975
00:37:34,780 --> 00:37:37,040
write down an action for this,

976
00:37:37,240 --> 00:37:39,240
literally thinking of it

977
00:37:39,240 --> 00:37:40,980
as a collection of mass points

978
00:37:40,980 --> 00:37:42,000
and,

979
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:42,480
um,

980
00:37:42,480 --> 00:37:43,480
and springs.

981
00:37:44,540 --> 00:37:45,160
Now,

982
00:37:45,160 --> 00:37:46,080
let's assume

983
00:37:46,780 --> 00:37:48,060
that the separation,

984
00:37:48,340 --> 00:37:50,060
let's call the horizontal axis

985
00:37:50,060 --> 00:37:51,140
the x-axis.

986
00:37:53,020 --> 00:37:55,840
Notice that x labels a point,

987
00:37:56,160 --> 00:37:58,340
but it is not itself a coordinate

988
00:37:58,340 --> 00:37:59,140
of the system.

989
00:37:59,260 --> 00:38:00,600
The phi's are the coordinates.

990
00:38:00,600 --> 00:38:02,080
The things which are the q's

991
00:38:02,860 --> 00:38:04,080
are the phi's.

992
00:38:04,280 --> 00:38:07,280
They represent the dynamical degrees of freedom.

993
00:38:07,460 --> 00:38:09,100
They represent what you need to know

994
00:38:09,100 --> 00:38:10,040
in order to get started.

995
00:38:10,480 --> 00:38:11,620
The x's,

996
00:38:12,419 --> 00:38:14,960
the x just labels which one you're talking about.

997
00:38:15,320 --> 00:38:16,900
This is x equals whatever.

998
00:38:17,180 --> 00:38:18,580
This is x equals twice whatever,

999
00:38:18,780 --> 00:38:19,480
three times whatever.

1000
00:38:20,960 --> 00:38:25,440
And let's assume that the distance

1001
00:38:25,440 --> 00:38:28,080
between neighboring points

1002
00:38:28,600 --> 00:38:29,880
along the x-axis

1003
00:38:30,600 --> 00:38:30,840
is equal to zero.

1004
00:38:30,840 --> 00:38:31,900
Let's call that epsilon.

1005
00:38:32,860 --> 00:38:34,220
At the end of the day,

1006
00:38:34,280 --> 00:38:35,980
we're going to add more and more and more

1007
00:38:35,980 --> 00:38:37,120
mass points

1008
00:38:37,880 --> 00:38:39,980
and shrink epsilon to zero

1009
00:38:39,980 --> 00:38:42,500
in such a way that they continue

1010
00:38:43,120 --> 00:38:45,440
to stretch between x equals zero

1011
00:38:45,440 --> 00:38:48,020
and x equals whatever the end point is here.

1012
00:38:49,680 --> 00:38:51,840
So as we add more and more mass points,

1013
00:38:52,040 --> 00:38:53,460
we'll shrink the gap.

1014
00:38:54,140 --> 00:38:54,660
Now,

1015
00:38:54,660 --> 00:38:55,280
first question,

1016
00:38:55,460 --> 00:38:57,540
what should we take to be the mass

1017
00:38:57,540 --> 00:38:59,300
of the ith point?

1018
00:39:00,600 --> 00:39:02,860
Imagine we took the mass to be a gram

1019
00:39:02,860 --> 00:39:05,060
or a kilogram or whatever.

1020
00:39:05,460 --> 00:39:07,980
As we add more and more mass points

1021
00:39:07,980 --> 00:39:09,330
and fill up the gaps

1022
00:39:09,330 --> 00:39:10,680
with more and more mass points,

1023
00:39:11,390 --> 00:39:13,540
it's pretty clear that the mass of that string

1024
00:39:13,540 --> 00:39:14,800
is going to become infinite

1025
00:39:14,800 --> 00:39:16,620
as we add more and more mass points

1026
00:39:16,620 --> 00:39:20,600
if the mass per particle is fixed.

1027
00:39:21,740 --> 00:39:23,140
What we're going to want to do

1028
00:39:23,140 --> 00:39:25,880
is imagine that a segment of string

1029
00:39:26,600 --> 00:39:28,920
has a overall mass

1030
00:39:28,920 --> 00:39:30,800
which doesn't change

1031
00:39:30,800 --> 00:39:32,780
as you add more and more points.

1032
00:39:33,020 --> 00:39:34,100
To do that,

1033
00:39:34,100 --> 00:39:35,140
we're going to have to shrink

1034
00:39:35,140 --> 00:39:37,240
the mass of the mass points

1035
00:39:37,240 --> 00:39:38,840
as we add more particles.

1036
00:39:39,780 --> 00:39:40,760
In particular,

1037
00:39:40,760 --> 00:39:41,940
we'll have to assume

1038
00:39:41,940 --> 00:39:43,860
that the mass of the ith particle

1039
00:39:45,720 --> 00:39:47,600
is proportional to epsilon.

1040
00:39:47,940 --> 00:39:49,180
Let's just call it epsilon.

1041
00:39:51,100 --> 00:39:51,980
The distance.

1042
00:39:52,380 --> 00:39:55,180
As epsilon shrinks smaller and smaller

1043
00:39:55,180 --> 00:39:57,760
and we crowd more and more mass points in there,

1044
00:39:57,760 --> 00:39:59,660
we'll shrink the masses

1045
00:39:59,660 --> 00:40:03,160
so that the net mass between two points

1046
00:40:03,160 --> 00:40:05,160
on the x-axis here stays fixed.

1047
00:40:06,860 --> 00:40:09,160
That means the mass of the ith point

1048
00:40:09,160 --> 00:40:11,380
is proportional to epsilon as it shrinks.

1049
00:40:12,100 --> 00:40:13,040
Let's just take it,

1050
00:40:13,040 --> 00:40:14,020
all the mass points,

1051
00:40:14,100 --> 00:40:16,980
to be the same mass of size epsilon.

1052
00:40:17,960 --> 00:40:20,020
Let's write down the kinetic energy.

1053
00:40:20,220 --> 00:40:23,460
The kinetic energy is the energy of motion

1054
00:40:24,160 --> 00:40:25,800
along the phi axis,

1055
00:40:26,040 --> 00:40:27,740
which means the vertical axis here.

1056
00:40:27,760 --> 00:40:29,080
What is it?

1057
00:40:30,100 --> 00:40:33,280
The kinetic energy is one half

1058
00:40:33,280 --> 00:40:36,300
the mass of the ith particle.

1059
00:40:36,900 --> 00:40:37,460
Well,

1060
00:40:37,460 --> 00:40:37,880
first of all,

1061
00:40:37,880 --> 00:40:38,660
we're going to have to sum.

1062
00:40:38,820 --> 00:40:40,240
We'll eventually sum.

1063
00:40:43,060 --> 00:40:44,820
Summation over all the particles.

1064
00:40:45,440 --> 00:40:47,180
The mass of the ith particle,

1065
00:40:47,180 --> 00:40:48,100
which is epsilon.

1066
00:40:48,980 --> 00:40:51,080
And then the square of the velocity,

1067
00:40:51,760 --> 00:40:52,500
which is,

1068
00:40:52,500 --> 00:40:52,940
after all,

1069
00:40:52,940 --> 00:40:53,980
just phi dot squared,

1070
00:40:54,300 --> 00:40:55,900
phi sub i dot squared,

1071
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:57,680
divided by two.

1072
00:40:57,760 --> 00:41:02,180
One half mass times the velocity squared.

1073
00:41:03,940 --> 00:41:07,240
That epsilon is in a rather convenient place

1074
00:41:07,240 --> 00:41:08,320
for later purposes.

1075
00:41:08,720 --> 00:41:10,360
Let me tell you what the later purposes are.

1076
00:41:11,520 --> 00:41:12,480
Later on,

1077
00:41:12,480 --> 00:41:14,400
we're going to replace this sum

1078
00:41:14,400 --> 00:41:15,900
by an integral.

1079
00:41:16,680 --> 00:41:18,210
When we start filling this up

1080
00:41:18,210 --> 00:41:19,740
with more and more dense points,

1081
00:41:19,940 --> 00:41:21,600
the sum is going to turn into an integral.

1082
00:41:21,740 --> 00:41:22,240
That's obvious.

1083
00:41:22,640 --> 00:41:24,480
Let me just remind you of the relation

1084
00:41:24,480 --> 00:41:26,080
between sums and integrals.

1085
00:41:26,080 --> 00:41:28,160
If we have a function

1086
00:41:30,080 --> 00:41:31,360
on an axis,

1087
00:41:31,680 --> 00:41:34,720
and the interval between neighboring points

1088
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:36,960
is,

1089
00:41:36,960 --> 00:41:37,460
well,

1090
00:41:37,460 --> 00:41:38,360
whatever that interval is,

1091
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:39,440
let's call it delta x,

1092
00:41:42,900 --> 00:41:45,780
then the definition of an integral,

1093
00:41:47,360 --> 00:41:48,500
f dx,

1094
00:41:49,540 --> 00:41:51,040
is just a summation

1095
00:41:52,260 --> 00:41:54,760
over all the values of the functions

1096
00:41:54,760 --> 00:41:56,060
at all these discrete points,

1097
00:41:56,060 --> 00:41:58,080
summation over i,

1098
00:41:58,700 --> 00:42:01,480
of the value of the function at the i-th point,

1099
00:42:02,160 --> 00:42:03,400
call it x sub i,

1100
00:42:03,580 --> 00:42:05,320
times delta x.

1101
00:42:07,020 --> 00:42:08,740
That's what this dx is there.

1102
00:42:08,900 --> 00:42:11,280
That dx really means delta x.

1103
00:42:12,480 --> 00:42:13,080
And,

1104
00:42:13,080 --> 00:42:13,820
of course,

1105
00:42:13,980 --> 00:42:16,040
f of x times delta of x

1106
00:42:16,040 --> 00:42:17,760
is just the area under that.

1107
00:42:18,840 --> 00:42:20,980
Height f with delta.

1108
00:42:22,800 --> 00:42:23,880
I have a question.

1109
00:42:24,120 --> 00:42:24,540
Yeah.

1110
00:42:24,540 --> 00:42:32,040
When you say that x labels the points,

1111
00:42:33,339 --> 00:42:36,160
would that be something like

1112
00:42:38,720 --> 00:42:42,760
x equals x zero plus i epsilon?

1113
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:50,180
I know what you're asking.

1114
00:42:50,580 --> 00:42:52,540
The x is,

1115
00:42:52,540 --> 00:42:52,980
of course,

1116
00:42:52,980 --> 00:42:54,540
at this point,

1117
00:42:55,420 --> 00:42:56,500
are discrete.

1118
00:42:57,560 --> 00:42:58,280
All right?

1119
00:42:58,300 --> 00:43:00,700
There's not a particle at every x.

1120
00:43:00,860 --> 00:43:03,760
There's a particle at a discrete collection of x's.

1121
00:43:05,240 --> 00:43:08,220
The allowable x's that correspond to particles

1122
00:43:08,919 --> 00:43:11,720
are separated by an interval epsilon.

1123
00:43:12,080 --> 00:43:13,880
I think that's roughly what you're asking.

1124
00:43:14,140 --> 00:43:14,520
Well,

1125
00:43:14,520 --> 00:43:16,120
i is already an index,

1126
00:43:16,360 --> 00:43:17,040
and x is...

1127
00:43:17,040 --> 00:43:17,140
Yeah,

1128
00:43:17,140 --> 00:43:17,280
yeah,

1129
00:43:17,280 --> 00:43:18,180
there's a redundant...

1130
00:43:18,180 --> 00:43:18,520
That's right.

1131
00:43:18,560 --> 00:43:22,500
There's a redundancy of notations here.

1132
00:43:22,980 --> 00:43:25,600
I could choose to label a particle by i,

1133
00:43:25,780 --> 00:43:27,110
or I could choose to

1134
00:43:27,110 --> 00:43:28,440
label it by x sub i.

1135
00:43:29,640 --> 00:43:31,620
The reason I have the redundancy

1136
00:43:31,620 --> 00:43:35,220
is to reinforce in your mind,

1137
00:43:35,280 --> 00:43:36,000
first of all,

1138
00:43:36,020 --> 00:43:38,240
that we're just talking about different particles.

1139
00:43:38,420 --> 00:43:39,200
That's the i index.

1140
00:43:39,520 --> 00:43:40,680
But later on,

1141
00:43:40,680 --> 00:43:41,680
we're going to take a limit

1142
00:43:42,660 --> 00:43:43,980
where the identity,

1143
00:43:44,260 --> 00:43:45,960
the discrete identity of the particle

1144
00:43:45,960 --> 00:43:48,500
is going to be replaced by a continuous identity

1145
00:43:48,500 --> 00:43:51,880
of degrees of freedom labeled by x.

1146
00:43:51,880 --> 00:43:53,100
It will no longer be a

1147
00:43:53,100 --> 00:43:54,320
good idea to label them by i.

1148
00:43:54,500 --> 00:43:55,780
We'll label them by x.

1149
00:43:56,340 --> 00:43:57,100
But x,

1150
00:43:57,100 --> 00:43:58,200
at this point,

1151
00:43:58,240 --> 00:44:00,860
x and x sub i are sort of redundant descriptions

